UPDATE events SET description = '<p>CAC&#8217;s Professional Development series works to uncover subjects critical to professional artists and curators outside of making art.</p>
<p>Dreaming Through Spreadsheets</p>
<p>Led by artist and creative entrepreneur Hope Wang, Dreaming Through Spreadsheets is a proposal to artists that spreadsheets, data visualization, and mind-mapping can be generative (and fun)! During this workshop, we will explore different organizational systems for project tracking, budget building, and creating maps of the pre-existing resources at our fingertips. Artists can often fixate on what we don’t have and how that’s keeping us from our goals, instead of seeing the merit of what resources are already available to us. By meticulously documenting and making visible the invisible costs that sustain artist practices, can we consider the budget spreadsheet or the planning document as a love letter to our ideas?</p>
<p>The structure of this workshop will be:</p>
<p>30 minute slide presentation: Practical mindsets on artists as the top funders of the art world + contextualization of sample diagrams and templates used for arts admin.<br>
30 minute guided exercise: Hope will call on 2 volunteers in the workshop for a live demonstration of two templates: Drawing your Dream Studio and Building a Grant Narrative. We will break down the cost of your dreams, no matter how large!<br>
45 minute breakout groups: Participants will articulate artistic goals and select templates to fill out together.</p>
<p>Who is this for? Artists who are looking for practical approaches to grant narratives, thinking through a project budget, preparing for new professional opportunities, and/or navigating change in your practice. Bring your own systems and favorite tools (and stationary) to share!</p>
<p>CAC&#8217;s Professional Development series works to uncover subjects critical to professional artists outside of making art.</p>
<p>Rooted in our core values of knowledge-sharing and building community, this 90-minute seminar will include 30 minutes of conversation with participants. Bring your experience and your questions to the group!</p>
<p>Participants may attend in person or online via Zoom. Registration is required.</p>
<p>Tuesday, February 24th 6-8p</p>
<p>$10 for the general public<br>
$5 for CAC alumni<br>
FREE for current residents</p>
<p><a href="https://www.hopewang.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.hopewang.com/</a></p>
<p>Hope Wang is an artist and creative entrepreneur based in Chicago, IL. Her practice explores memory, loss, and longing in the ever-shifting architectural landscape. Hope is also the founder and co-director of LMRM “loom room,” is a project space fostering opportunities for art-making, research, and community programming around digital weaving. She is invested in equitable conditions for working artists, resource sharing, and moving at the speed of trust. She is a two-time recipient of an Artists Run Chicago Grant (2024 &amp; 2025) from the Hyde Park Art Center, and a Chicago Community Fellowship Fund (2023) from the Breakout Foundation for LMRM’s contributions to the city’s art community. Her artwork has been exhibited throughout the US, which includes the Glass Curtain Gallery at Columbia College Chicago, IL; the Peeler Art Center at DePauw University in Greencastle, IN; The Villa Terrace Decorative Arts Museum in Milwaukee, WI; amongst others.</p>
 <p>
 <a>Official Website</a>
 </p>' WHERE id = 'bcfc78a3-9929-48d3-ab68-de052968b714';
UPDATE events SET description = '<p>From the multitude of definitions, surrealism readily encapsulates the rejection of rationalism and the embrace of imagination, creating an intriguing baseline. UNREAL draws upon a variety of the machinations that evoke the multiplicities of the original 1920s cultural movement conceived by artist André Breton with his Surrealist Manifesto in 1924 and “officially” ending with Jean Schuster’s provocative manifesto The Fourth Song in 1969. Unofficially, however, the power of imagination has never been for naught; creative freedom has expanded the concept of surrealism beyond a singular artistic movement, instead realizing it as a persistent state of mind.</p>
<p>One hundred years later, the core principles of surrealism still revolve around dreamlike narratives, symbolic iconography, distorted or abstract humor, illusionistic play of materials and mediums, and the stretching of rationality in pursuit of liberation. UNREAL takes a flexible, contemporaneous interpretation of these ideologies while keeping a wary eye on the complexities of current socio-political, conceptual, and philosophical concerns. While the origins of the movement evolved from a combination of the horrors of war alongside the burgeoning field of Sigmund Freud’s analysis of the subconscious, its influence continues to adapt and resonate within contemporary artistic practice today.</p>
<p>The diverse approaches to reality presented in UNREAL foreground a synchronous mode of art-making characteristic of contemporary practices. The works explore themes of fantasy, mystery, history, family, spirituality, identity, and sexuality, situating them within frameworks that initially presume coherence and legibility. However, with varying degrees of opacity and inexplicability, these artworks can destabilize these assumptions, complicating the viewer’s capacity to distinguish between the real and the constructed.</p>
<p>This tension produces a critical space in which reality is not approached as a fixed or stable condition, but as a mediated construct. The exhibition reflects broader ideological shifts in society in which truth claims &#8211; understood as assertions upheld by individuals, belief systems, or authoritative texts &#8211; are increasingly coming under scrutiny. Instead, we find ourselves in a place where multiple narratives can exist and subjective experiences are validated. By extolling the concept of ambiguity, UNREAL resists singular interpretation and instead foregrounds the instability of meaning itself. In this sense, the exhibition may be understood as an inquiry into the clarity of the image itself as it relates to the limits of representation. Here, reality is not merely depicted but is instead produced, refracted, and reconfigured through aesthetic and discursive practices.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Featured artists:<br>
Esaí Alfredo<br>
Dan Attoe<br>
Ever Baldwin<br>
Omar Barquet<br>
Chris Bradley<br>
Ginny Casey<br>
Josh Dihle<br>
Al Freeman<br>
Nereida Garcia-Ferraz<br>
Lola Gil<br>
Naomi Hawksley<br>
Jared McGriff<br>
Kitty Rauth<br>
Nina Surel</p>
 <p>
 <a>Official Website</a>
 </p>' WHERE id = 'bfc49d2b-4fe6-4629-8cd1-d15ef4d1d6a1';
